Rule.desc: Avoid hard-coding the arguments to certain methods
Avoid using insecure cryptographic algorithms for data encryption with Spring
Avoid using insecure cryptographic algorithms in Spring XML configurations
Keep all access control methods centralized to enforce consistency
Keep all authentication methods centralized to enforce consistency
Always clone array parameters which are stored to fields
Avoid using cryptographic keys which are too short
Avoid constructors and overriding methods which are more accessible than those of their super classes
Inspect usage of standard API calls that bypass security
Allow only certain providers to be specified for the 'Security.addProvider()' method
Prevent external processes from blocking on output or error streams
Only call "final" methods from specified code blocks in non-"final" classes
Do not define custom class loaders

CategoryGroup.desc: This represents the findings arising from tests that have already been reviewed. This includes exceptions that have been marked as expected, assertion failures from previously reviewed tests, and any other kind of unexpected behavior that needs to be looked at (such as timeouts).
CategoryGroup.label: Fix Unit Test Problems
CategoryGroup.name: Unit Test Problems

CategoryGroup.desc: These are exceptions thrown by automatically generated test cases that need to be reviewed. After review they will be marked as "expected" or code fixed so that the exception does not occur any more.
CategoryGroup.label: Review Exceptions
CategoryGroup.name: Exceptions

CategoryGroup.desc: These are assertion failures from automatically generated tests that have not been reviewed. This is expected to be zero when the tests are executed as soon as they are generated, but can be non-zero in cases where tests that have not been reviewed, but the execution is repeated.
CategoryGroup.label: Review Assertion Failures
CategoryGroup.name: Assertion Failures
